\fs40 \cf4 Key Points\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0
\fs32 \cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ServiceLoader is NOT persistent - it just finds classes and creates instances\
\ls12\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ServiceLoader only works in same JVM - can't use it across process boundaries\
\ls12\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
DIRECT mode benefits most - typed interface, no reflection in your code\
\ls12\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
ATTACHED/DETACHED modes - typically just call 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf16 \cb17 main()
\fs32 \cf4 \cb1  in forked process\
\ls12\ilvl0\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Bootstrap option - if you want ServiceLoader in forked processes too, use a bootstrap main class\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 The beauty is: DIRECT mode gets clean typed calls, while forked modes use standard 
\fs28\fsmilli14400 \cf16 \cb17 java -cp ... MainClass
\fs32 \cf4 \cb1  approach that works everywhere.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
